          "body": "The chapter's moral hinge is a single verb in a single verse: Daniel 'made up his mind' (literally 'set upon his heart') that he would not defile himself with the king's food or wine. Scholars debate the specific rationale for the food refusal — proposed explanations include: (a) the food was not slaughtered according to Mosaic law (Leviticus 11; 17:10-14); (b) the food may have been dedicated to Babylonian deities before consumption; (c) accepting the king's table carried covenantal and social obligations Daniel was unwilling to assume; (d) Daniel was operating from a broader principle of covenant non-assimilation, using food as the test-case. The text does not specify which; all four may be operative. What the text does make clear is that Daniel drew the line before the pressure arrived — he 'made up his mind,' a resolve that predates the conversation with Ashpenaz (1:8-10), not a reaction formed in the moment. He also drew the line wisely: he did not refuse the Chaldean curriculum (1:4, 17), did not refuse his Babylonian name in official contexts, and did not stage a public protest. He identified the precise point where compliance became defilement and held that line with both courage and tact."
