        "body": "The opening two verses establish the chapter's governing theological claim before a single human character acts. Verse 1 reads like a straightforward military chronicle — Nebuchadnezzar besieged Jerusalem. Verse 2 is the interpretive key: the LORD gave Jehoiakim into his hand. The same formula appears in Jeremiah 20:4-5 (the LORD giving Judah into Nebuchadnezzar's hand), Jeremiah 25:8-11 (the LORD naming Nebuchadnezzar 'my servant' and announcing 70 years of captivity), and Lamentations 1:5 (the LORD afflicting Jerusalem for her many sins). Daniel is not departing from the prophetic tradition; he is confirming it. The fall of Jerusalem is not a failure of divine power but an exercise of divine judgment.\n\nThe placement of the temple vessels is theologically charged. The *keli* (vessels, articles) of the house of God (Israel's *elohim*) are carried to the house of Nebuchadnezzar's *elohim* and deposited in his treasury. In the ancient Near East, the capture of a god's cult objects was understood as proof that the conquering deity had defeated the defending deity. Nebuchadnezzar's action is a theological claim: Marduk has overcome Yahweh. The rest of Daniel's twelve chapters refutes that claim in episode after episode — but the refutation begins here, in the narrator's choice to name the LORD as the one who gave. The victor of verse 1 is the instrument of verse 2's actual Agent.\n\nThe use of *Shinar* rather than *Babylon* (a deliberate archaism in the Hebrew text) invokes Genesis 10:10 and 11:2 — the land of Babel, where humanity first organized itself in rebellion against God. Daniel's audience would have caught the resonance immediately: the exile is not merely a political catastrophe; it is a return to the spiritual geography of the world's first anti-God project. And yet God was sovereign over Babel (Genesis 11:7-8), as He is sovereign over Babylon now.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Adonai* (v.2, 'the LORD') is the divine title emphasizing sovereignty and lordship — Daniel's choice of *Adonai* rather than the covenant name *YHWH* may be deliberate, emphasizing God's universal sovereign rule over empires, not merely His covenant relationship with Israel. *Natan* ('gave') — the same verb used of God giving gifts (wisdom, favor) later in the chapter — here used of God giving a king into judgment. The same hand that judges gives grace."
