        "body": "Verses 3-7 describe Nebuchadnezzar's assimilation program with bureaucratic precision. Three mechanisms are deployed in sequence: education (1:4 — Chaldean literature and language), provision (1:5 — royal food and wine), and renaming (1:7 — Babylonian names replacing Hebrew ones). Each mechanism targets a different dimension of identity: education reshapes the mind, provision creates social obligation and dependency, and renaming erases the theological significance encoded in the Hebrew names.\n\nThe selection criteria of verse 4 are worth dwelling on. Nebuchadnezzar did not want average captives; he wanted the intellectual and social elite of the conquered nation. This was standard imperial policy — Rome would later do the same with provincial aristocrats. The strategy is sophisticated: recruit the best, invest in them, and make them advocates for the empire within their own communities. Daniel and his friends are chosen precisely because they are exceptional. Their very exceptionalism makes the chapter's conclusion more striking — when God gifts them beyond the empire's capacity to produce, He is vindicating not their mediocrity but their excellence.\n\nThe renaming of verse 7 is the program's most theologically significant act. Daniel's Hebrew name means 'God is my judge' (*Dan* = judge, *El* = God). His Babylonian name Belteshazzar likely means 'May Bel protect his life' — invoking Bel/Marduk. Hananiah means 'Yahweh is gracious'; Shadrach may invoke Aku, the moon god. Mishael means 'Who is what God is?' — an implicit monotheistic confession; Meshach may be a Babylonian divine name. Azariah means 'Yahweh has helped'; Abed-nego means 'servant of Nego' (Nabu, a Babylonian deity of wisdom and writing). The renaming is a systematic theological replacement — every Hebrew name that confesses the God of Israel is replaced with a name that invokes a Babylonian deity. Yet the narrator consistently uses the Hebrew names throughout the chapter (note vv. 6, 11, 17, 19), refusing the Babylonian substitution at the narrative level. The author signals his allegiance by the names he chooses to use.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Shem* (name, v.7) in Hebrew carries identity-weight beyond simple designation — a name is what a person *is*. Renaming in the ancient world was a claim of ownership and authority (cf. God renaming Abram and Jacob; Pharaoh renaming Joseph in Genesis 41:45). Babylon is not merely changing labels; it is claiming to own and define these young men."
