        "body": "The chapter's closing verse is a single temporal statement that functions as a theological thesis. Daniel 'continued' (Hebrew *amad* — stood, remained, persisted) until the first year of Cyrus the king (539 BC). This is a span of more than 65 years from his initial captivity in 605 BC. Nebuchadnezzar, the chapter's dominant human figure, is dead. The Babylonian empire, which seemed invincible in 605 BC, has fallen. Daniel stands.\n\nThe verb *amad* (to stand) is used three times in this chapter — of the youths entering the king's service (1:5, 19: 'stand before the king') and here of Daniel's career-long persistence (1:21). The chapter that began with a king standing over captured Jerusalem ends with a captive of that king still standing when the king's empire is gone. The reversal is total and is entirely God's work — Daniel did not outlast Babylon by his own resilience; he outlasted it because the God who gave Jehoiakim into Nebuchadnezzar's hand also gave Daniel wisdom, favor, and a ministry that spanned empires.\n\nThe mention of Cyrus is significant beyond chronology. Cyrus is the Persian king whom Isaiah had prophesied by name more than a century before his birth (Isaiah 44:28; 45:1) — the one whom the LORD would use to issue the decree permitting Jewish exiles to return and rebuild Jerusalem. Daniel's ministry, which began when Babylon took Jerusalem, closes with the arrival of the king through whom God would begin to restore it. The captive outlasted the captor; the servant of God outlasted the servant of Marduk; the one who refused to defile himself with Babylon's food was still standing when Babylon itself was consumed.\n\nFor the book's original readers — and for every subsequent generation of God's people living under pressure from a dominant world-system — verse 21 is the chapter's most important encouragement. What Daniel modeled is not merely a dietary discipline; it is a long obedience in the same direction (Eugene Peterson's phrase captures it well). The empires of this world are temporary. The servant who refuses to be assimilated by them, trusting the sovereignty of the God who governs them, will outlast them. Not in his own strength, but in the strength of the One who gives, again and again, the favor, wisdom, and endurance needed for the moment."
